LUCRETIUS V. 512—25

parti : archaic abl. for parte. See note on 1. 74. polum is the object, aera the subject of premere. 512. tenere, ‘ confines it.’

utrimque, ‘at both ends.' That is to say, the sphere of heaven revolves on its axis; this axis must be kept steady, which is done by two currents of air pressing each pole (each end of the axis) on the outside and keeping the axis firm in its place ; then ll. 513—14 to make the sphere revolve we must have a third current of air, which may blow on the poles above the sphere in the direction in which the sphere moves, or ll. 515—16 it may blow underneath the sphere in the opposite direction.
